Title:
Broken Audit Integrity: User Can Modify EntryUser Field and Tamper Audit Trail

Description:
The application allows a user to modify the entryUser field when performing certain actions. This field, which is expected to represent the actual authenticated user performing the action, is being taken from client-side input rather than being set securely on the server side. As a result, any user can impersonate another user in the audit trail by modifying this field, leading to false attribution of actions and compromising the reliability of logs.

Impact:
Audit Trail Tampering: Malicious users can mislead investigators or administrators by falsifying who performed an action.

Accountability Loss: The system can no longer reliably identify users responsible for changes or activities.

Potential for Insider Threat Cover-Up: A user could perform malicious actions while attributing them to another legitimate user, avoiding detection.

Steps to Reproduce:
Log in as a valid user (e.g., User A).

Perform an action that triggers an audit trail entry (e.g., creating or updating a record).

Intercept the request using a proxy like Burp Suite.

Locate the entryUser or similar field in the request payload.

Modify the value to another username or arbitrary string (e.g., "admin", "superuser", or even an emoji).

Forward the request and observe the response.

Check the audit logs or history UI—notice that the action is attributed to the spoofed entryUser value.

Remediation:
Remove any client-supplied entryUser or similar fields from trust.

On the server side, always set the acting user’s name from the authenticated session or token.

Sanitize and validate all audit log inputs.

Ensure audit mechanisms are tamper-proof and trustworthy.
